### 1. One-Line Summary
* Dignics 05 is a high-ceiling, high-spin “power” rubber with strong stability at high impact, while Rakza 7 Soft is a more forgiving, softer ESN-style rubber that’s easier to engage and control in the short game.


### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:**
        * Dignics 05: Needs cleaner acceleration to “wake up”; lower gear is usable but can feel less bouncy than typical ESN, rewarding proper brushing.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Engages quickly with minimal effort; noticeably easier to produce depth and pace on compact strokes.
    * **Top End:**
        * Dignics 05: Higher ceiling; excels when you commit with full body and heavy acceleration—stronger finishing power from mid/far distance.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Lower ceiling; tops out earlier when you swing hard, with less outright pace and bite at maximum power.
    * **Linearity:**
        * Dignics 05: More “geared”; moderate step-up from medium to high impact, but very predictable once you’re used to it.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: More linear at low-to-medium impact; at very high impact it can feel slightly mushy/compressed.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:**
        * Dignics 05: Strong on heavy brush openings, especially vs backspin, but demands good timing and racket speed.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Very easy to open with; soft sponge helps lift underspin with less perfect technique.
    * **Max Spin:**
        * Dignics 05: Higher max spin potential on full, fast swings; excellent for loaded third-ball and rally loops.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: High spin for its class, but absolute peak rotation is lower than Dignics 05 at top gear.
    * **Topsheet Grip:**
        * Dignics 05: Very grippy and stable under strong contact; holds spin well during high-speed brushing.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Grippy and friendly, but the softer foundation can slightly reduce “bite” under extreme power.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:**
        * Dignics 05: Medium-high arc with strong arc stability when you accelerate; produces a heavy, dipping ball.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Medium to medium-high arc; naturally “lifts” the ball, especially on slower loops.
    * **Safety:**
        * Dignics 05: High safety at higher impact (arc holds); at low impact, you must supply quality brush to keep it safe.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: High safety in low-to-mid gears; more forgiving when you’re late or not fully set.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:**
        * Dignics 05: Firm, crisp, and direct; clear feedback but less “cushion” on thin contact.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Soft, cushioned, and comfortable; easy to feel the ball, especially for developing touch.
    * **Dwell:**
        * Dignics 05: Moderate dwell with a firm base; dwell is “earned” by proper brushing and acceleration.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Longer perceived dwell from softness; helps with spin creation and control at slower pace.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:**
        * Dignics 05: Spin-sensitive, especially on receives and flicks; rewards good angle discipline.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Also spin-sensitive but easier to dampen with the soft sponge; simpler to keep serves short.
    * **Touch Play:**
        * Dignics 05: Excellent once trained—precise pushes and stop shots, but punishes sloppy touch.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Easier touch and drop shots; more margin for error on pushes and short blocks.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:**
        * Dignics 05: Very stable if your angle is correct; firm feel can pop the ball up if you’re passive and misread spin.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Softer absorption makes passive blocking easier; can bottom out against heavy power if you don’t firm up.
    * **Active Counter:**
        * Dignics 05: Excellent for punchy counters and counterloops; converts incoming pace into a heavy, fast ball.
        * Rakza 7 Soft: Strong at close-table counters with good control; less authoritative in counterloop exchanges from distance.

* **Choose Dignics 05 if:**
    * You play a modern topspin game and often finish points with full strokes (mid-distance included).
    * You want the highest ceiling for spin and power and can generate your own acceleration consistently.
    * You value crisp feedback and stability when counterlooping or trading heavy topspin.

* **Choose Rakza 7 Soft if:**
    * You want easier access to speed/spin with compact strokes and a more forgiving learning curve.
    * Your priorities are short game comfort, opening consistency, and controlled close-table play.
    * You prefer a softer feel for blocking, touch, and allround-to-offensive progression.


### 3. The Recommendation
* For advanced attackers who train often, use strong acceleration, and want top-tier spin/power stability: pick Dignics 05.
* For players who want a softer, easier rubber that boosts opening success and short-game control without demanding perfect technique: pick Rakza 7 Soft.